    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-12-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-12-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="684"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d684">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/26787½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the President’s Personal Representative to Pope
                        Pius XII</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Taylor</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-12-12">December 12,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Apostolic Delegate<note n="51" xml:id="d684fn51">Archbishop Amleto Giovanni
                        Cicognani.</note> telephoned me this morning and I called upon him. He has a
                    further inquiry from the Vatican in respect to the question of bombing Rome,
                    indicating impatience at the Vatican because we have not definitely communicated
                    to the Holy See the suggestions which you and Archbishop Spellman<note n="52"
                        xml:id="d684fn52">Francis Joseph Spellman, Archbishop of New York.</note>
                    and myself have discussed with the President. He is indicating in his reply that
                    the matter is receiving active attention requiring consultation with the Allied
                    Command and the British. I made no definite statement but did express the hope
                    that some policy might be evolved, but whatever it is, future conduct would have
                    to be governed by the eventualities of the war, and further that Italy should
                    not provoke such an attack by any act of her own.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>M[<hi rend="smallcaps">yron</hi>] C. T[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >aylor</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
